<fr:tree toc="true" numbered="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
  <fr:frontmatter>
    <fr:anchor>713</fr:anchor>
    <fr:addr type="user">FA-001L</fr:addr>
    <fr:route>FA-001L.xml</fr:route>
    <fr:title text="Measurable function">Measurable function</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors />
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, \mathcal {A})]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(Y, \mathcal {B})]]></fr:tex> be measurable spaces, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {A}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {B}]]></fr:tex> are σ-algebras on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, respectively. A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: X \to  Y]]></fr:tex> is said to be measurable if the preimage of every measurable set in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is a measurable set in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>Formally, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {A}]]></fr:tex>-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {B}]]></fr:tex> measurable if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(B) \in  \mathcal {A}]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B \in  \mathcal {B}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>In the context of real-valued functions on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex>, a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: \mathbb {R}^d \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is Lebesgue measurable if the preimage of every Borel set in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is a Lebesgue measurable set in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>Equivalently, a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: \mathbb {R}^d \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is Lebesgue measurable if and only if the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x \in  \mathbb {R}^d : f(x) > a\}]]></fr:tex> is Lebesgue measurable for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a \in  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Backlinks">Backlinks</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>714</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001D</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001D.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Almost everywhere">Almost everywhere</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A property is said to hold almost everywhere (abbreviated as "a.e.") on a measure space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, \mathcal {A}, \mu )]]></fr:tex> if the set of points where the property fails has measure zero.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Formally, a property <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> holds almost everywhere if there exists a measurable set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[μ(N) = 0]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> holds for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X \setminus  N]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>This concept is fundamental in measure theory and functional analysis because it allows us to ignore sets of measure zero, which are often irrelevant for integration and other analytical purposes.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For example, two <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable functions</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> are said to be equal almost everywhere if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mu (\{x \in  X : f(x) \neq  g(x)\}) = 0]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>715</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0029</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0029.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Essential supremum">Essential supremum</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>For a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> defined on a measure space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, \Sigma , \mu )]]></fr:tex>, the essential supremum is the smallest value that bounds <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> almost everywhere.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Formally, the essential supremum of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {ess} \sup  f]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_{L^\infty }]]></fr:tex>, is defined as:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_{L^\infty } = \inf \{M \in  \mathbb {R} : |f(x)| \leq  M \text { for almost all } x \in  X\}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>where "almost all" means "except possibly on a set of measure zero".</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The essential supremum differs from the regular supremum in that it ignores the values of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> on sets of measure zero. This is crucial in the theory of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> spaces, particularly <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^\infty ]]></fr:tex>, which consists of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable functions</fr:link> that are bounded almost everywhere.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For example, if we modify a function at a single point, this changes its supremum but not its essential supremum (since a single point has Lebesgue measure zero).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The essential supremum is used to define the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^\infty ]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0018.xml" addr="FA-0018" title="Norm">norm</fr:link>, making <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^\infty ]]></fr:tex> a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000F.xml" addr="FA-000F" title="Banach Space">Banach space</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>716</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001Y</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001Y.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hölder inequality">Hölder inequality</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f, g : E \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable functions</fr:link>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p, q \in  [1, +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001W.xml" addr="FA-001W" title="Conjugate exponents">conjugate</fr:link>. Then</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[||fg||_{L^1(E)} \leq  ||f||_{L^p(E)} ||g||_{L^q(E)}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>The proof uses <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001X.xml" addr="FA-001X" title="Young's Inequality">Young's Inequality</fr:link></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Remark</fr:strong> Hölder inequality can be also rephrased as follows:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\int _E |f(x)|^\alpha  |g(x)|^\beta  dx \leq  \left (\int _E |f(x)| dx\right )^\alpha  \left (\int _E |g(x)| dx\right )^\beta ]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>provided <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha  + \beta  = 1]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Discrete case</fr:strong> Let</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = (x_1, \dots , x_n), y = (y_1, \dots , y_n) \in  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p, q \in  {1,2,3 \dots }]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1/p + 1/q = 1]]></fr:tex>, then</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\sum _{i=1}^n |x_i y_i| \leq  \left (\sum _{i=1}^n |x_i|^p\right )^{1/p} \left (\sum _{i=1}^n |y_i|^q\right )^{1/q}]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>717</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001N</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001N.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Lebesgue integral">Lebesgue integral</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The Lebesgue integral is a generalization of the Riemann integral that allows for the integration of a broader class of functions. It is defined for <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable functions</fr:link> on a measure space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, \mathcal {A}, \mu )]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The construction of the Lebesgue integral proceeds in several steps:</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li>First, define the integral for non-negative <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001O.xml" addr="FA-001O" title="Simple function">simple functions</fr:link> (finite linear combinations of indicator functions of measurable sets).</fr:li>
<fr:li>Then, extend this definition to non-negative measurable functions using monotone approximation by simple functions.</fr:li>
<fr:li>Finally, define the integral for general measurable functions by separately integrating their positive and negative parts.</fr:li></fr:ol>
            <fr:p>The Lebesgue integral has many advantages over the Riemann integral:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>It allows for the integration of a larger class of functions</fr:li>
<fr:li>It has better convergence properties, exemplified by the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001F.xml" addr="FA-001F" title="Monotone Convergence Theorem">Monotone Convergence Theorem</fr:link> and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001E.xml" addr="FA-001E" title="Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem">Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem</fr:link></fr:li>
<fr:li>It provides a more natural setting for limiting operations and for the study of function spaces like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> spaces</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>718</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001E</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001E.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem">Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_k : \mathbb {R}^d \to  [-\infty , +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> be a sequence of measurable functions. Suppose that</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li>There exists a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : \mathbb {R}^d \to  [-\infty , +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_n \to  f]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001D.xml" addr="FA-001D" title="Almost everywhere">almost everywhere</fr:link>.</fr:li>
<fr:li>There exists a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001M.xml" addr="FA-001M" title="Summable">summable</fr:link> function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g : \mathbb {R}^d \to  [-\infty , +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f_n(x)| \leq  g(x)]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> and for <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001D.xml" addr="FA-001D" title="Almost everywhere">almost every</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  \mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ol>
            <fr:p>Then,</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[{\int  f(x)dx = \lim _{n \to  +\infty } \int  f_n(x)dx}]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>719</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-002A</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-002A.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Lp norm">Lp norm</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p < +\infty ]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega  \subset  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> be a Lebesgue <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable set</fr:link>. For a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: \Omega  \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> we define the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> norm of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> as the (finite or infinite) number</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_{L^p(\Omega )} \stackrel {\text {def}}{=} \left (\int _{\Omega } |f(x)|^p dx\right )^{1/p}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Moreover, we set</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C \stackrel {\text {def}}{=} \{\alpha  \in  \mathbb {R} : |f(x)| \leq  \alpha  \text { almost everywhere on } \Omega \}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^\infty ]]></fr:tex> norm of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> (also called the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0029.xml" addr="FA-0029" title="Essential supremum">essential supremum</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>) is defined as</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_{L^\infty (\Omega )} = \inf  C]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>720</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001Z</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001Z.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Minkowski's inequality">Minkowski's inequality</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f, g : E \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable functions</fr:link>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \in  [1, +\infty ]]]></fr:tex>. Then,</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[||f+g||_{L^p(E)} \leq  ||f||_{L^p(E)} + ||g||_{L^p(E)}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Proof uses <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001Y.xml" addr="FA-001Y" title="Hölder inequality">Hölder inequality</fr:link></fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>721</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001F</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001F.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Monotone Convergence Theorem">Monotone Convergence Theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_k : \mathbb {R}^d \to  [0, +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> be a sequence of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable function</fr:link>s. Assume that</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[f_n(x) \leq  f_{n+1}(x) \quad  \text {almost everywhere}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Then, there exists <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : \mathbb {R}^d \to  [0, +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001B.xml" addr="FA-001B" title="Measurable set">measurable</fr:link> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_n \to  f]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001D.xml" addr="FA-001D" title="Almost everywhere">almost everywhere</fr:link>, and</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[{\lim _{n \to  +\infty } \int  f_n(x)dx = \int  f(x)dx.}]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>722</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001O</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001O.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Simple function">Simple function</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A simple function (or simple measurable function) is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable function</fr:link> that takes only a finite number of values. Specifically, a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s: X \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> (or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>) defined on a measure space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, \mathcal {A}, \mu )]]></fr:tex> is a simple function if it can be written as:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(x) = \sum _{i=1}^n a_i \chi _{E_i}(x)]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_1, a_2, \ldots , a_n]]></fr:tex> are constants, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_1, E_2, \ldots , E_n]]></fr:tex> are measurable sets, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\chi _{E_i}]]></fr:tex> is the indicator function of the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_i]]></fr:tex> (which equals 1 on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_i]]></fr:tex> and 0 elsewhere).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Simple functions play a crucial role in the construction of the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001N.xml" addr="FA-001N" title="Lebesgue integral">Lebesgue integral</fr:link>, as they serve as the building blocks for more general measurable functions. Any non-negative measurable function can be approximated by an increasing sequence of simple functions.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>723</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001M</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001M.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Summable">Summable</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: X \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> (or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>) defined on a measure space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, \mathcal {A}, \mu )]]></fr:tex> is said to be summable if it is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable</fr:link> and its <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001N.xml" addr="FA-001N" title="Lebesgue integral">Lebesgue integral</fr:link> is finite:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\int _X |f(x)| d\mu (x) < \infty ]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>In the context of the Lebesgue measure on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex>, a function is summable if it is in the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^1(\mathbb {R}^d)]]></fr:tex>, i.e., if the integral of its absolute value over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex> is finite.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Summable functions are precisely those functions for which the Lebesgue integral exists and is finite.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
</fr:tree>
